off in terms of helping

00:50:52.440 --> 00:50:55.930
our evolution as a society.

00:50:55.930 --> 00:50:59.231
I certainly think
that, I mean, I

00:50:59.231 --> 00:51:00.980
argue that the meeting
and mating of ideas

00:51:00.980 --> 00:51:03.210
is what produces innovation.

00:51:03.210 --> 00:51:07.500
And that's why
you get innovation

00:51:07.500 --> 00:51:11.160
in places with a lot of trade
throughout history, Renaissance

00:51:11.160 --> 00:51:17.115
Italy, [INAUDIBLE] China,
Fuji and Chinese people,

00:51:17.115 --> 00:51:18.240
Gujarat in India, you know.

00:51:18.240 --> 00:51:20.300
Wherever there's
been a lot of trade,

00:51:20.300 --> 00:51:22.710
you tend to get a
lot of innovation.

00:51:22.710 --> 00:51:26.200
Victorian England, Holland in
the Golden Age, California,

00:51:26.200 --> 00:51:28.280
today-- you know, et cetera.

00:51:28.280 --> 00:51:33.750
And so places where people
can meet other people freely

00:51:33.750 --> 00:51:37.570
and invest and be free to do
what they want and then change

00:51:37.570 --> 00:51:40.200
ideas are terribly important.

00:51:40.200 --> 00:51:43.010
And we've just created a
virtual one of those that's

00:51:43.010 --> 00:51:45.070
global-- or very nearly global.

00:51:45.070 --> 00:51:47.060
Almost everybody
is involved in it.

00:51:47.060 --> 00:51:50.090
And that has to be accelerating
the rate of evolution

00:51:50.090 --> 00:51:52.550
because a man in
Shanghai can swap ideas

00:51:52.550 --> 00:51:54.720
with a man in San
Francisco today-- or sorry,

00:51:54.720 --> 00:51:57.590
a woman in San
Francisco can swap ideas

00:51:57.590 --> 00:52:04.760
with a woman in Shanghai today
just as in a millisecond.

00:52:04.760 --> 00:52:07.360
They don't have to
catch a-- get on a ship

00:52:07.360 --> 00:52:09.690
and go and meet each
other, et cetera.

00:52:09.690 --> 00:52:11.690
And even compared
with 20 years ago,

00:52:11.690 --> 00:52:13.960
the rate at which ideas
are meeting other ideas

00:52:13.960 --> 00:52:16.220
must be accelerating.

00:52:16.220 --> 00:52:18.590
And that's why I'm slightly
puzzled we're not yet

00:52:18.590 --> 00:52:21.530
seeing what my friends
at Singularity University

00:52:21.530 --> 00:52:24.460
say is going to happen,
this incredible acceleration

00:52:24.460 --> 00:52:25.850
of technology.

00:52:25.850 --> 00:52:27.574
And part of the
problem is we run up

00:52:27.574 --> 00:52:29.740
against diminishing returns
in certain technologies.

00:52:29.740 --> 00:52:31.990
So transport has changed
very little in my lifetime,

00:52:31.990 --> 00:52:35.040
whereas communication
has changed enormously.

00:52:35.040 --> 00:52:38.655
Opposite in my grandparents'
time, communication

00:52:38.655 --> 00:52:41.030
changed very little in the
first half of the 20th century

00:52:41.030 --> 00:52:42.779
but transport changed
pretty dramatically.

00:52:45.300 --> 00:52:52.144
So yes, I think we are
generating possibilities.

00:52:52.144 --> 00:52:53.560
I certainly don't
think innovation

00:52:53.560 --> 00:52:54.690
is going to slow down.

00:52:54.690 --> 00:52:57.150
And if you look at the
growth of world GDP,

00:52:57.150 --> 00:53:00.130
it's unbelievably steady.

00:53:00.130 --> 00:53:01.720
There's one year
since Second World

00:53:01.720 --> 00:53:05.920
War when it was negative--
2009, by less than 1%.

00:53:05.920 --> 00:53:07.380
It grew by 5% the next year.

00:53:07.380 --> 00:53:10.290
So it was back on track.

00:53:10.290 --> 00:53:12.277
It's just like
this straight line.

00:53:12.277 --> 00:53:13.860
But actually, when
you think about it,

00:53:13.860 --> 00:53:16.960
because it's a percentage
thing, that straight line

00:53:16.960 --> 00:53:18.430
means it's an exponential thing.

00:53:18.430 --> 00:53:21.230
Means it's accelerating
all the time.

00:53:21.230 --> 00:53:24.100
And you extrapolate that
to the end of this century,

00:53:24.100 --> 00:53:27.380
and the average person on the
planet will be about 15 times

00:53:27.380 --> 00:53:27.930
as rich.

00:53:27.930 --> 00:53:29.430
No, sorry, will be
about three times

00:53:29.430 --> 00:53:32.340
as rich as the average
American is today.

00:53:32.340 --> 00:53:36.270
Those are unbelievable numbers
when you think about it.

00:53:36.270 --> 00:53:38.340
And sure, there's a
lot could go wrong.

00:53:38.340 --> 00:53:40.580
And we could hit some
brick walls along the way.

00:53:40.580 --> 00:53:44.000
But if that doesn't
happen, the potential

00:53:44.000 --> 00:53:46.680
for what we can do with
innovation for the human race

00:53:46.680 --> 00:53:52.124
is truly amazing I
think-- which might

00:53:52.124 --> 00:53:54.040
be a good moment on which
to end because we've

