00:54:27.260 --> 00:54:27.850
yep, yep.

00:54:27.850 --> 00:54:29.600
AUDIENCE: Just as an
organizing principle

00:54:29.600 --> 00:54:32.300
so that you can mobilize
resources and actually

00:54:32.300 --> 00:54:33.570
accomplish things.

00:54:33.570 --> 00:54:38.600
So I'm curious to hear your, you
know-- where you see actually

00:54:38.600 --> 00:54:42.880
these hierarchies being useful
as opposed to being encumbering

00:54:42.880 --> 00:54:45.120
things, like, for example,
they did make efforts

00:54:45.120 --> 00:54:48.500
to sort of standardize language
so that we can actually speak

00:54:48.500 --> 00:54:50.420
a common language,
even though that

00:54:50.420 --> 00:54:53.250
might have been a natural
process that it came from.

00:54:53.250 --> 00:54:56.500
There seems to be these
two forces of top down,

00:54:56.500 --> 00:54:59.080
us trying to organize
things, and then bottom up,

00:54:59.080 --> 00:55:00.130
things kind of happening.

00:55:00.130 --> 00:55:02.519
So my question is, how do you
kind of reconcile the two?

00:55:02.519 --> 00:55:04.810
MATT RIDLEY: Is there anything
top down about language?

00:55:04.810 --> 00:55:05.010
I'm--

00:55:05.010 --> 00:55:07.170
AUDIENCE: Sure, yeah, I mean,
there are opposing forces

00:55:07.170 --> 00:55:07.961
in language, right.

00:55:07.961 --> 00:55:10.730
There's the natural linguistic
laws that shape language

00:55:10.730 --> 00:55:13.230
but then there are groups of
people coming together, saying,

00:55:13.230 --> 00:55:15.688
like, we're all going to agree
to call this a chair and not

00:55:15.688 --> 00:55:16.900
a fafafa, you know, whatever.

00:55:16.900 --> 00:55:19.840
Because you guys over there call
it one way, we call it another.

00:55:19.840 --> 00:55:22.790
We have to agree-- we agree
implicitly but also explicitly

00:55:22.790 --> 00:55:25.069
through, like, standardization
of how to call things.

00:55:25.069 --> 00:55:26.860
MATT RIDLEY: That's
still pretty bottom up.

00:55:26.860 --> 00:55:30.190
That's still ordinary people
kind of voting among themselves

00:55:30.190 --> 00:55:33.680
rather than any
hierarchical body.

00:55:33.680 --> 00:55:35.510
Now, it's true
the French set out

00:55:35.510 --> 00:55:39.520
to standardize French
language and to extinguish

00:55:39.520 --> 00:55:41.770
non French speakers
within their territory,

00:55:41.770 --> 00:55:44.440
you know-- force them, as it
were, to switch to French,

00:55:44.440 --> 00:55:44.940
as it were.

00:55:44.940 --> 00:55:46.356
And they still
have this committee

00:55:46.356 --> 00:55:48.170
that tries to decide
whether you're allowed

00:55:48.170 --> 00:55:51.774
to stay "le weekend" or not.

00:55:51.774 --> 00:55:52.940
But it doesn't get very far.

00:55:52.940 --> 00:55:56.550
And look at Esperanto,
that's a top down attempt

00:55:56.550 --> 00:55:59.440
to create a language--
didn't get very far.

00:55:59.440 --> 00:56:01.630
So I would challenge
you that there

00:56:01.630 --> 00:56:05.881
is really anything very top down
or hierarchical about language.

00:56:05.881 --> 00:56:07.130
AUDIENCE: Couldn't it be both?

00:56:07.130 --> 00:56:09.700
Because it doesn't have to be
the government or a large body.

00:56:09.700 --> 00:56:12.200
It could be a group of people
getting together and agreeing,

00:56:12.200 --> 00:56:13.905
though, saying that this is--

00:56:13.905 --> 00:56:14.800
MATT RIDLEY: Is that
really happening?

00:56:14.800 --> 00:56:16.430
I mean, when did
